<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910222-0143</DOCNO><DOCID>910222-0143.</DOCID><HL>   Bouygues S.A. Says   Goldman Sachs Sold   Stake in TV Station   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>02/22/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3B</SO><CO>   F.BOU F.CLC F.SGF U.MXC</CO><IN>TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)</IN><LP>   PARIS -- French construction company Bouygues S.A., theprincipal shareholder in French television station TF1, saidU.S. investment bank Goldman, Sachs andamp; Co. sold its recentlyacquired 10% stake in the station to a group of Bouyguesallies.   A Bouygues spokeswoman said the 2.6 million shares weresold yesterday at 290 French francs ($57) a share. TF1 stockclosed yesterday at 287 francs a share.</LP><TEXT>   Goldman Sachs had bought the shares from U.K. investorRobert Maxwell. However, the sale was in apparent violationof a TF1 core shareholders' pact that gave the core groupfirst refusal rights on any sale of the TV station's stock.   Bouygues filed a petition Tuesday against Mr. Maxwell atthe Paris commercial court, but the suit has been dropped asa result of the latest agreement.   Goldman Sachs said it agreed to sell the shares to a groupcomprising Credit Lyonnais, Societe Generale, Banque Indosuezand Groupe Worms andamp; Co., all of which are French financialgroups.   Bouygues couldn't buy the shares from either Mr. Maxwellor Goldman Sachs because it had reached the legal limit of25%, the maximum investment allowed in a private French TVstation.</TEXT></DOC>